<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-669-846  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 669 846.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  July 23 1990 v7 n29 p1(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>IBM releases power-cord fix for 55SX PS/2s.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Sexton, Tara.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>IBM is urging owners of the company's popular PS/2 55SXmicrocomputer to check their systems for the existence a powercord that may be defective.andP;  According to IBM's estimates, 'tensof thousands' of PS/2 55SXs are equipped with a cord made byMultilec S.A.andP;  of Mexico that may cause irregular power streams oreven a complete loss of power.andP;  Only two defective cords have beenreported so far, but IBM plans to replace all Multilec cords as aprecaution.andP;  An IBM official says that those 55SX systems alreadyup and running should not be affected by the glitch, but thatowners should contact an authorized IBM dealer.andP;  The dealer willreplace the cord, on-site, free of charge.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (customer relations)Multilec S.A. (products).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Product:   IBM PS/2 55 SX (Microcomputer) (defects).andO;Topic:     DefectsPower FailureCablesMicrocomputers.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   IBM's power cord recall. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Tara SextonandM;IBM is replacing the power cord on tens of thousands of its PS/2 Model 55SXcomputers to remedy a reported wiring problem, company officials confirmedlast week.andM;Users of IBM's best-selling PS/2 should check their power cord for a Multileclabel, according to Robert Carberry, vice president of systems for IBM'sEntry Systems Division in Somers, N.Y.andP;  PS/2s equipped with this cord,manufactured by Multilec S.A., of Mexico, may experience irregular powerstreams or a complete loss of power, he said.andM;According to IBM's estimates, &quot;tens of thousands&quot; of PS/2 Model 55SXs featurethe Multilec cord.andP;  While the company suspects that only a small number ofthese cords are defective -- only two cases have been reported so far -- itplans to replace all of them as a precaution, Carberry said.andP;  Model 55SXusers with the Multilec cord should contact an IBM authorized dealer, whowill replace the cord on-site and free of charge, he said.andM;&quot;There is no chance of personal injury,&quot; Carbury stressed, &quot;but we want ourcustomers to take this seriously.&quot;andM;Scott Meuller, an instructor at the American Institute, a New York-basedcomputer training company, concurred that users will not risk electricalshock by handling or using the faulty equipment.andM;Others agreed.andP;  &quot;The problem is inside the wire, and that's prettywell-insulated,&quot; said an independent systems engineer for a large computerretail chain who requested anonymity.andP;  &quot;The hazard is to your computer.&quot;andM;A sudden power outage could cause data to be lost, and an irregular supply ofpower could damage PC components such as the monitor or the disk drive, theengineer explained.andM;&quot;Users with a defective cable will know right away,&quot; Carberry said.andP;  &quot;Themachine will simply not power up.&quot;andM;Users already up and running on a Model 55SX with a Multilec cable probablywon't be affected by the glitch.andP;  However, Carberry cautions these users notto reconfigure or move their systems because it could cause a defective cableto malfunction; he also suggested that they contact an authorized IBM dealerfor the fix.andO;</TEXT></DOC>